# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adiabatic-quantum-motor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/adiabatic-quantum-motor] An **adiabatic quantum motor** is a mechanical device, typically nanometric, driven by a flux of quantum particles and able to perform cyclic motions.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/adiabatic-quantum-motor] The adjective "adiabatic" in this context refers to the limit when the dynamics of the mechanical degrees of freedom is slow compared with the dwell time of the particles passing through the device.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/adiabatic-quantum-motor] In this regime, it is commonly assumed that the mechanical degrees of freedom behave classically.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/adiabatic-quantum-motor] This class of devices works essentially as quantum pumps operated in reverse.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/adiabatic-quantum-motor] While in a quantum pump, the periodic movement of some parameters pumps quantum particles from one reservoir to another, in a quantum motor a DC current of particles induces the cyclic motion of the device.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/adiabatic-quantum-motor] One key feature of these motors is that quantum interferences can be used to increase their efficiency by enhancing the reflection coefficient of the scattered particles.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/adiabatic-quantum-motor] Although there are several proposals for the realization of adiabatic quantum motors, none of them have been verified experimentally.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The abbreviations *AC* and *DC* are often used to mean simply *alternating* and *direct*, as when they modify *current* or *voltage*.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Direct current may be converted from an alternating current supply by use of a rectifier, which contains electronic elements (usually) or electromechanical elements (historically) that allow current to flow only in one direction.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Direct current may be converted into alternating current via an inverter.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Direct current has many uses, from the charging of batteries to large power supplies for electronic systems, motors, and more.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Very large quantities of electrical energy provided via direct-current are used in smelting of aluminum and other electrochemical processes.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] It is also used for some railways, especially in urban areas.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] High-voltage direct current is used to transmit large amounts of power from remote generation sites or to interconnect alternating current power grids.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Direct current was produced in 1800 by Italian physicist Alessandro Volta's battery, his Voltaic pile.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The nature of how current flowed was not yet understood.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] French physicist André-Marie Ampère conjectured that current travelled in one direction from positive to negative.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] When French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii built the first dynamo electric generator in 1832, he found that as the magnet used passed the loops of wire each half turn, it caused the flow of electricity to reverse, generating an alternating current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] At Ampère's suggestion, Pixii later added a commutator, a type of "switch" where contacts on the shaft work with "brush" contacts to produce direct current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The late 1870s and early 1880s saw electricity starting to be generated at power stations.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] These were initially set up to power arc lighting (a popular type of street lighting) running on very high voltage (usually higher than 3,000 volts) direct current or alternating current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] This was followed by the widespread use of low voltage direct current for indoor electric lighting in business and homes after inventor Thomas Edison launched his incandescent bulb based electric "utility" in 1882.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Because of the significant advantages of alternating current over direct current in using transformers to raise and lower voltages to allow much longer transmission distances, direct current was replaced over the next few decades by alternating current in power delivery.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] In the mid-1950s, high-voltage direct current transmission was developed, and is now an option instead of long-distance high voltage alternating current systems.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] For long distance undersea cables (e.g. between countries, such as NorNed), this DC option is the only technically feasible option.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] For applications requiring direct current, such as third rail power systems, alternating current is distributed to a substation, which utilizes a rectifier to convert the power to direct current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The term *DC* is used to refer to power systems that use only one electrical polarity of voltage or current, and to refer to the constant, zero-frequency, or slowly varying local mean value of a voltage or current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] For example, the voltage across a DC voltage source is constant as is the current through a direct current source.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The DC solution of an electric circuit is the solution where all voltages and currents are constant.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Any stationary voltage or current waveform can be decomposed into a sum of a DC component and a zero-mean time-varying AC component; the DC component is defined to be the expected value, or the average value of the voltage or current over all time.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Although DC stands for "direct current", DC often refers to "constant polarity".
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Under this definition, DC voltages can vary in time, as seen in the raw output of a rectifier or the fluctuating voice signal on a telephone line.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Some forms of DC (such as that produced by a voltage regulator) have almost no variations in voltage, but may still have variations in output power and current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] A direct current circuit is an electrical circuit that consists of any combination of constant voltage sources, constant current sources, and resistors.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] In this case, the circuit voltages and currents are independent of time.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] A particular circuit voltage or current does not depend on the past value of any circuit voltage or current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] This implies that the system of equations that represent a DC circuit do not involve integrals or derivatives with respect to time.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] If a capacitor or inductor is added to a DC circuit, the resulting circuit is not, strictly speaking, a DC circuit.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] However, most such circuits have a DC solution.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] This solution gives the circuit voltages and currents when the circuit is in DC steady state.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Such a circuit is represented by a system of differential equations.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The solution to these equations usually contain a time varying or transient part as well as constant or steady state part.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] It is this steady state part that is the DC solution.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] There are some circuits that do not have a DC solution.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Two simple examples are a constant current source connected to a capacitor and a constant voltage source connected to an inductor.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] In electronics, it is common to refer to a circuit that is powered by a DC voltage source such as a battery or the output of a DC power supply as a DC circuit even though what is meant is that the circuit is DC powered.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] In a DC circuit, a power source (e.g. a battery, capacitor, etc.) has a positive and negative terminal, and likewise, the load also has a positive and negative terminal.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] To complete the circuit, positive charges need to flow from the power source to the load.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The charges will then return to the negative terminal of the load, which will then flow back to the negative terminal of the battery, completing the circuit.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] If either the positive or negative terminal is disconnected, the circuit will not be complete and the charges will not flow.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] In some DC circuit applications, polarity does not matter, which means you can connect positive and negative backwards and the circuit will still be complete and the load will still function normally.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] However, in most DC applications, polarity does matter, and connecting the circuit backwards will result in the load not working properly.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] DC is commonly found in many extra-low voltage applications and some low-voltage applications, especially where these are powered by batteries or solar power systems (since both can produce only DC).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Most electronic circuits or devices require a DC power supply.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Domestic DC installations usually have different types of sockets, connectors, switches, and fixtures from those suitable for alternating current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] This is mostly due to the lower voltages used, resulting in higher currents to produce the same amount of power.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] It is usually important with a DC appliance to observe polarity, unless the device has a diode bridge to correct for this.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] An automotive battery provides power for engine starting, lighting, the ignition system, the climate controls, and the infotainment system among others.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The alternator is an AC device which uses a rectifier to produce DC for battery charging.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Most highway passenger vehicles use nominally 12 V systems.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Many heavy trucks, farm equipment, or earth moving equipment with Diesel engines use 24 volt systems.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] In some older vehicles, 6 V was used, such as in the original classic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] At one point a 42 V electrical system was considered for automobiles, but this found little use.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] To save weight and wire, often the metal frame of the vehicle is connected to one pole of the battery and used as the return conductor in a circuit.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Often the negative pole is the chassis "ground" connection, but positive ground may be used in some wheeled or marine vehicles.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] In a battery electric vehicle, there are usually two separate DC systems.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The "low voltage" DC system typically operates at 12V, and serves the same purpose as in an internal combustion engine vehicle.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The "high voltage" system operates at 300-400V (depending on the vehicle), and provides the power for the traction motors.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Increasing the voltage for the traction motors reduces the current flowing through them, increasing efficiency.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Telephone exchange communication equipment uses standard −48 V DC power supply.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] The negative polarity is achieved by grounding the positive terminal of power supply system and the battery bank.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] This is done to prevent electrolysis depositions.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Telephone installations have a battery system to ensure power is maintained for subscriber lines during power interruptions.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Other devices may be powered from the telecommunications DC system using a DC-DC converter to provide any convenient voltage.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Many telephones connect to a twisted pair of wires, and use a bias tee to internally separate the AC component of the voltage between the two wires (the audio signal) from the DC component of the voltage between the two wires (used to power the phone).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems use DC for the bulk transmission of electrical power, in contrast with the more common alternating current systems.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] For long-distance transmission, HVDC systems may be less expensive and suffer lower electrical losses.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Applications using fuel cells (mixing hydrogen and oxygen together with a catalyst to produce electricity and water as byproducts) also produce only DC.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/dc-current] Light aircraft electrical systems are typically 12 V or 24 V DC similar to automobiles.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] A **pump** is an alternating current-driven device that generates a direct current (DC).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In the simplest configuration a pump has two leads connected to two reservoirs.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In such open geometry, the pump takes particles from one reservoir and emits them into the other.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Accordingly, a current is produced even if the reservoirs have the same temperature and chemical potential.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Pumping and stirring effects in quantum physics have counterparts in purely classical stochastic and dissipative processes.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The studies of quantum pumping and of quantum stirring emphasize the role of quantum interference in the analysis of the induced current.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] A major objective is to calculate the amount Q of transported particles per a driving cycle.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] There are circumstances in which Q is an integer number due to the topology of parameter space.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] More generally Q is affected by inter-particle interactions, disorder, chaos, noise and dissipation.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Electric stirring explicitly breaks time-reversal symmetry.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] This property can be used to induce spin polarization in conventional semiconductors by purely electric means.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Strictly speaking, stirring is a non-linear effect, because in linear response theory (LRT) an AC driving induces an AC current with the same frequency.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Still an adaptation of the LRT Kubo formalism allows the analysis of stirring.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The quantum pumping problem (where we have an open geometry) can be regarded as a special limit of the quantum stirring problem (where we have a closed geometry).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Optionally the latter can be analyzed within the framework of scattering theory.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Pumping and Stirring devices are close relatives of ratchet systems.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The latter are defined in this context as AC driven spatially periodic arrays, where DC current is induced.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] It is possible to induce a DC current by applying a bias, or if the particles are charged then by applying an electro-motive-force.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In contrast to that a quantum pumping mechanism produces a DC current in response to a cyclic deformation of the confining potential.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In order to have a DC current from an AC driving, time reversal symmetry (TRS) should be broken.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In the absence of magnetic field and dissipation it is the driving itself that can break TRS.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Accordingly, an adiabatic pump operation is based on varying more than one parameter, while for non-adiabatic pumps modulation of a single parameter may suffice for DC current generation.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The best known example is the peristaltic mechanism that combines a cyclic squeezing operation with on/off switching of entrance/exit valves.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Adiabatic quantum pumping is closely related to a class of current-driven nanomotors named Adiabatic quantum motor.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] While in a quantum pump, the periodic movement of some classical parameters pumps quantum particles from one reservoir to another, in a quantum motor a DC current of quantum particles induce the cyclic motion of the classical device.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] where j and $\alpha$ are indexes over the mechanical degrees of freedom and the leads respectively, and the subindex " $eq$ " implies that the quantities should be evaluated at equilibrium, i.e. ${\dot {X}}=0$ and $\delta \mu =0$ .
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Consider a closed system which is described by a Hamiltonian ${\mathcal {H}}(X)$ that depends on some control parameters $X=(X_{1},X_{2},X_{3})$ .
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] If $X_{3}$ is an Aharonov Bohm magnetic flux through the ring, then by Faraday law $-{\dot {X_{3}}}$ is the electro motive force.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] If linear response theory applies we have the proportionality $I=-G^{33}{\dot {X}}_{3}$ , where $G^{33}$ is the called the Ohmic conductance.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The conductance can be calculated and analyzed using the Kubo formula approach to quantum pumping, which is based on the theory of adiabatic processes.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] where ${\mathcal {I}}$ is the current operator, and ${\mathcal {F}}^{j}=-\partial {\mathcal {H}}/\partial X_{j}$ is the generalized force that is associated with the control parameter $X_{j}$ .
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Though this formula is written using quantum mechanical notations it holds also classically if the commutator is replaced by Poisson brackets.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In general G can be written as a sum of two terms: one has to do with dissipation, while the other, denoted as B has to do with geometry.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The dissipative part vanishes in the strict quantum adiabatic limit, while the geometrical part B might be non-zero.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] It turns out that in the strict adiabatic limit B is the "Berry curvature" (mathematically known as ``two-form").
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] where we define the normal vector ${\vec {ds}}=(dX_{2},-dX_{1})$ as illustrated.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The advantage of this point of view is in the intuition that it gives for the result: Q is related to the flux of a field ${\vec {B}}$ which is created (so to say) by "magnetic charges" in X space.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] This formula can be regarded as the quantum adiabatic limit of the Kubo formula.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The eigenstates of the system are labeled by the index n .
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] These are in general many body states, and the energies are in general many body energies.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] At finite temperatures a thermal average over $n_{0}$ is implicit.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The field B can be regarded as the rotor of "vector potential" A (mathematically known as the "one-form").
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Accordingly, one can argue that the "magnetic charge" that generates (so to say) the B field consists of quantized "Dirac monopoles".
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] It follows from gauge invariance that the degeneracies of the system are arranged as vertical Dirac chains.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The "Dirac monopoles" are situated at X points where $n_{0}$ has a degeneracy with another level.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The Dirac monopoles picture is useful for charge transport analysis: the amount of transported charge is determined by the number of the Dirac chains encircled by the pumping cycle.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Optionally it is possible to evaluate the transported charge per pumping cycle from the Berry phase by differentiating it with respect to the Aharonov–Bohm flux through the device.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The Ohmic conductance of a mesoscopic device that is connected by leads to reservoirs is given by the Landauer formula: in dimensionless units the Ohmic conductance of an open channel equals its transmission.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The extension of this scattering point of view in the context of quantum pumping leads to the Brouwer-Buttiker-Pretre-Thomas (BPT) formula which relates the geometric conductance to the S matrix of the pump.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Here $P_{A}$ is a projector that restrict the trace operations to the open channels of the lead where the current is measured.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] This BPT formula has been originally derived using a scattering approach, but later its relation to the Kubo formula has been worked out.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] A very recent work considers the role of interactions in the stirring of Bose condensed particles.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Otherwise the rest of the literature concerns primarily electronic devices.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Typically the pump is modeled as a quantum dot.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The effect of electron–electron interactions within the dot region is taken into account in the Coulomb blockade regime or in the Kondo regime.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In the former case charge transport is quantized even in the case of small backscattering.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] Deviation from the exact quantized value is related to dissipation.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In the Kondo regime, as the temperature is lowered, the pumping effect is modified.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] There are also works that consider interactions over the whole system (including the leads) using the Luttinger liquid model.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] A quantum pump, when coupled to classical mechanical degrees of freedom, may also induce cyclic variations of the mechanical degrees of freedom coupled to it.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] In such a configuration, the pump works similarly to an Adiabatic quantum motor.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] A paradigmatic example of this class of systems is a quantum pump coupled to an elastically deformable quantum dot.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/quantum-stirring-ratchets-and-pumping] The mentioned paradigm has been generalized to include non-linear effects and stochastic fluctuations.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] In physics and electrical engineering the **reflection coefficient** is a parameter that describes how much of a wave is reflected by an impedance discontinuity in the transmission medium.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] It is equal to the ratio of the amplitude of the reflected wave to the incident wave, with each expressed as phasors.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] For example, it is used in optics to calculate the amount of light that is reflected from a surface with a different index of refraction, such as a glass surface, or in an electrical transmission line to calculate how much of the electromagnetic wave is reflected by an impedance discontinuity.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient is closely related to the *transmission coefficient*.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The reflectance of a system is also sometimes called a reflection coefficient.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Different disciplines have different applications for the term.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] In telecommunications and transmission line theory, the reflection coefficient is the ratio of the complex amplitude of the reflected wave to that of the incident wave.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The voltage and current at any point along a transmission line can always be resolved into forward and reflected traveling waves given a specified reference impedance *Z0*.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The reference impedance used is typically the characteristic impedance of a transmission line that's involved, but one can speak of reflection coefficient without any actual transmission line being present.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] In terms of the forward and reflected waves determined by the voltage and current, the reflection coefficient is defined as the complex ratio of the voltage of the reflected wave ( $V^{-}$ ) to that of the incident wave ( $V^{+}$ ).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient may also be established using other field or circuit pairs of quantities whose product defines power resolvable into a forward and reverse wave.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] In the accompanying figure, a signal source with internal impedance $Z_{S}$ possibly followed by a transmission line of characteristic impedance $Z_{S}$ is represented by its Thévenin equivalent, driving the load $Z_{L}$ .
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] For a real (resistive) source impedance $Z_{S}$ , if we define $\Gamma$ using the reference impedance $Z_{0}=Z_{S}$ then the source's maximum power is delivered to a load $Z_{L}=Z_{0}$ , in which case $\Gamma =0$ implying no reflected power.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] More generally, the squared-magnitude of the reflection coefficient $|\Gamma |^{2}$ denotes the proportion of that power that is reflected back to the source, with the power actually delivered toward the load being $1-|\Gamma |^{2}$ .
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Anywhere along an intervening (lossless) transmission line of characteristic impedance $Z_{0}$ , the magnitude of the reflection coefficient $|\Gamma |$ will remain the same (the powers of the forward and reflected waves stay the same) but with a different phase.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] In the case of a short circuited load ( $Z_{L}=0$ ), one finds $\Gamma =-1$ at the load.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] This implies the reflected wave having a 180° phase shift (phase reversal) with the voltages of the two waves being opposite at that point and adding to zero (as a short circuit demands).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient is determined by the load impedance at the end of the transmission line, as well as the characteristic impedance of the line.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient can also be measured at other points on the line.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The *magnitude* of the reflection coefficient in a lossless transmission line is constant along the line (as are the powers in the forward and reflected waves).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] However its *phase* will be shifted by an amount dependent on the electrical distance $\phi$ from the load.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Note that the phase of the reflection coefficient is changed by *twice* the phase length of the attached transmission line.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] That is to take into account not only the phase delay of the reflected wave, but the phase shift that had first been applied to the forward wave, with the reflection coefficient being the quotient of these.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The reflection coefficient so measured, $\Gamma '$ , corresponds to an impedance which is generally dissimilar to $Z_{L}$ present at the far side of the transmission line.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The complex reflection coefficient (in the region $|\Gamma |\leq 1$ , corresponding to passive loads) may be displayed graphically using a Smith chart.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The Smith chart is a polar plot of $\Gamma$ , therefore the magnitude of $\Gamma$ is given directly by the distance of a point to the center (with the edge of the Smith chart corresponding to $|\Gamma |=1$ ).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Its evolution along a transmission line is likewise described by a rotation of $2\phi$ around the chart's center.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Using the scales on a Smith chart, the resulting impedance (normalized to $Z_{0}$ ) can directly be read.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Before the advent of modern electronic computers, the Smith chart was of particular use as a sort of analog computer for this purpose.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Along a lossless transmission line of characteristic impedance *Z*0, the SWR signifies the ratio of the voltage (or current) maxima to minima (or what it would be if the transmission line were long enough to produce them).
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The above calculation assumes that $\Gamma$ has been calculated using *Z*0 as the reference impedance.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Since it uses only the *magnitude* of $\Gamma$ , the SWR intentionally ignores the specific value of the load impedance *ZL* responsible for it, but only the magnitude of the resulting impedance mismatch.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] That SWR remains the same wherever measured along a transmission line (looking towards the load) since the addition of a transmission line length to a load $Z_{L}$ only changes the phase, not magnitude of $\Gamma$ .
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] While having a one-to-one correspondence with reflection coefficient, SWR is the most commonly used figure of merit in describing the mismatch affecting a radio antenna or antenna system.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] It is most often measured at the transmitter side of a transmission line, but having, as explained, the same value as would be measured at the antenna (load) itself.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] A transmission line is an example of a 2-port electrical network, but reflection coefficients are useful in the analysis of any electrical networks.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] A reflection coefficient for each port in the same way as for the boundary of a transmission line.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] It will, however, also depend on the properties of connections at other ports and so is not a property intrinsic to the network itself.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Reflection coefficient is used in feeder testing for reliability of medium.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] In optics and electromagnetics in general, *reflection coefficient* can refer to either the amplitude reflection coefficient described here, or the reflectance, depending on context.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Typically, the reflectance is represented by a capital *R*, while the amplitude reflection coefficient is represented by a lower-case *r*.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] These related concepts are covered by Fresnel equations in classical optics.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] Acousticians use reflection coefficients to understand the effect of different materials on their acoustic environments.
[src:adiabatic-quantum-motor/reflection-coefficient] The field properties used to define the reflection coefficient are typically the acoustic pressure and velocity in the incident and reflected acoustic waves.
